etymologies: early 17th century; earliest use found in Philemon Holland (1552–1637), translator. From classical Latin suburbium suburb + -an

definitions: suburban, specifically with reference to the immoral or licentious practices of the suburbs, especially of London; (now) of or relating to suburbia.

notes.text: In the 17th century the more common form; later superseded by suburban.

definitions: A person who resides in a suburb. Now also: a resident of suburbia.
